{"title_page": "Henry Reeve (soldier)", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2007}}\n\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Henry Mike Reeve Carroll\n|birth_date=  {{Birth-date|April 4th, 1850}}\n|death_date= August 4th, 1876 (aged 26)\n|birth_place=  [[New York City]], [[United States]]|\n|death_place= [[Yaguaramas]], [[Cuba]]\n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label=\n|image= Henry Reeve.jpg\n|image_size=150\n|caption='''Brigadier General Henry Reeve'''\n|nickname= El Inglesito (Little Englishman)\n|allegiance= {{Flagu|United States|1861}}<br />{{flag|Cuba}}\n|branch= {{Flagicon image|U.S. flag (35 stars).svg|size=23px}} [[Union Army]] (1861\u20131865)<br />{{flagicon|Cuba}} Cuban Army of Liberation (Cuba)<br />(1869-1876)\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= Soldier (U.S.)<br />Brigadier General (Cuba)\n|commands=\n|unit=\n|battles= [[American Civil War]]<br />[[Ten Years' War]] (Cuba)\n|awards=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n\n'''Henry Reeve''' (April 4, 1850 \u2014 August 4, 1876) was a [[Brigadier General]] in [[Cuba]]'s 'Ej\u00e9rcito Libertador' (Army of Liberation) - more commonly known as the '[[Ej\u00e9rcito Mamb\u00ed]]' - during the First Cuban War of Independence ([[Ten Years' War]]) (1868-1878). In his youth, he was a drummer boy in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States on April 4, 1850, son of Alexander Reeve and Maddie Carroll, and died in [[Matanzas Province|Matanzas]], Cuba on August 4, 1876.  Reeve was 26 years old at the time of his death, and had served in the [[Military of Cuba|Cuban Army]] for 7 years, having participated in over 400 engagements against the [[Spanish Army]]. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\nHenry Reeve was honored by the Cuban government in 1976 on the centenary of his death with a [[postal stamp|posta]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}[[postal stamp|l stamp]].\n\nIn response to Hurricane Katrina, Cuba assembled 1,586 humanitarian doctors to offer to assist the United States.  The offer was declined, and on September 19, 2005 Fidel Castro created the Henry Reeve International Contingent of Doctors Specialized in Disasters and Serious Epidemics in honor of him.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/WORLD/americas/09/05/katrina.cuba/ | work=CNN | title=Castro: U.S. hasn't responded to Katrina offer | accessdate=June 1, 2011}}</ref> In March 2020, 144 health workers from this Henry Reeve brigade were sent by Cuba to assist Jamaica in dealing with the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic |coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elmaazi |first1=Mohamed |title=Corbyn praises Cuba\u2019s \u2018inspirational\u2019 coronavirus efforts \u2013 part of its longstanding medical solidarity around the world |url=https://www.thecanary.co/uk/analysis/2020/03/26/corbyn-praises-cubas-inspirational-coronavirus-efforts-part-of-its-longstanding-medical-solidarity-around-the-world/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |publisher=The Canary |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Sources and further reading ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929125152/http://www.zmag.org/content/showarticle.cfm?ItemID=8788 Speech by Fidel Castro initiating the Henry Reeve's Contingent]\n*{{ecured|Henry Reeve}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reeve, Henry}}\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1876 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cuban soldiers]]\n[[Category:People of the Ten Years' War]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to Cuba]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=February 2007}}\n\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Henry Mike Reeve Carroll\n|birth_date=  {{Birth-date|April 4th, 1850}}\n|death_date= August 4th, 1876 (aged 26)\n|birth_place=  [[New York City]], [[United States]]|\n|death_place= [[Yaguaramas]], [[Cuba]]\n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label=\n|image= Henry Reeve.jpg\n|image_size=150\n|caption='''Brigadier General Henry Reeve'''\n|nickname= El Inglesito (Little Englishman)\n|allegiance= {{Flagu|United States|1861}}<br />{{flag|Cuba}}\n|branch= {{Flagicon image|U.S. flag (35 stars).svg|size=23px}} [[Union Army]] (1861\u20131865)<br />{{flagicon|Cuba}} Cuban Army of Liberation (Cuba)<br />(1869-1876)\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= Soldier (U.S.)<br />Brigadier General (Cuba)\n|commands=\n|unit=\n|battles= [[American Civil War]]<br />[[Ten Years' War]] (Cuba)\n|awards=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n\n'''Henry Reeve''' (April 4, 1850 \u2014 August 4, 1876) was a [[Brigadier General]] in [[Cuba]]'s 'Ej\u00e9rcito Libertador' (Army of Liberation) - more commonly known as the '[[Ej\u00e9rcito Mamb\u00ed]]' - during the First Cuban War of Independence ([[Ten Years' War]]) (1868-1878). In his youth, he was a drummer boy in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States on April 4, 1850, son of Alexander Reeve and Maddie Carroll, and died in [[Matanzas Province|Matanzas]], Cuba on August 4, 1876.  Reeve was 26 years old at the time of his death, and had served in the [[Military of Cuba|Cuban Army]] for 7 years, having participated in over 400 engagements against the [[Spanish Army]]. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n\n\n\n\n \n\n\nHenry Reeve was honored by the Cuban government in 1976 on the centenary of his death with a [[postal stamp]].\n\nIn response to Hurricane Katrina, Cuba assembled 1,586 humanitarian doctors to offer to assist the United States.  The offer was declined, and on September 19, 2005 Fidel Castro created the Henry Reeve International Contingent of Doctors Specialized in Disasters and Serious Epidemics in honor of him.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/WORLD/americas/09/05/katrina.cuba/ | work=CNN | title=Castro: U.S. hasn't responded to Katrina offer | accessdate=June 1, 2011}}</ref> In March 2020, 144 health workers from this Henry Reeve brigade were sent by Cuba to assist Jamaica in dealing with the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic |coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elmaazi |first1=Mohamed |title=Corbyn praises Cuba\u2019s \u2018inspirational\u2019 coronavirus efforts \u2013 part of its longstanding medical solidarity around the world |url=https://www.thecanary.co/uk/analysis/2020/03/26/corbyn-praises-cubas-inspirational-coronavirus-efforts-part-of-its-longstanding-medical-solidarity-around-the-world/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |publisher=The Canary |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Sources and further reading ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929125152/http://www.zmag.org/content/showarticle.cfm?ItemID=8788 Speech by Fidel Castro initiating the Henry Reeve's Contingent]\n*{{ecured|Henry Reeve}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reeve, Henry}}\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1876 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cuban soldiers]]\n[[Category:People of the Ten Years' War]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to Cuba]]\n", "name_user": "Lovemankind83", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Reeve_(soldier)"}
{"title_page": "Tyne and Wear County Council", "text_new": "{{Infobox legislature\n| name               = Tyne and Wear County Council\n| native_name        =\n| native_name_lang   =\n| transcription_name =\n| legislature        =\n| coa_pic            =Tyne-&-Wear-Flag.jpg\n| coa_caption        =\n| coa_res            =\n| coa_alt            =\n| logo_pic           =\n| logo_caption       =\n| logo_res           =\n| logo_alt           =\n| house_type         =\n| body               =\n| houses             =\n| term_limits        =\n| foundation         = 1 April 1974\n| disbanded          = 1 April 1986\n| preceded_by        =\n| succeeded_by       = {{nowrap|[[Metropolitan Borough of Gateshead]]}}<br>[[Newcastle City Council]]<br>[[North Tyneside Council]]<br>[[South Tyneside Council]]<br>[[Sunderland City Council]]\n| new_session        =\n| leader1_type       =\n| leader1            =\n| party1             =\n| election1          =\n| leader2_type       =\n| leader2            =\n| party2             =\n| election2          =\n| leader3_type       =\n| leader3            =\n| party3             =\n| election3          =\n| leader4_type       =\n| leader4            =\n| party4             =\n| election4          =\n| leader5_type       =\n| leader5            =\n| party5             =\n| election5          =\n| leader6_type       =\n| leader6            =\n| party6             =\n| election6          =\n| seats              =\n| house1             =\n| house2             =\n| structure1         =\n| structure1_res     =\n| structure1_alt     =\n| structure2         =\n| structure2_res     =\n| structure2_alt     =\n| political_groups1  =\n| political_groups2  =\n| committees1        =\n| committees2        =\n| joint_committees   =\n| voting_system1     =\n| voting_system2     =\n| last_election1     =\n| last_election2     =\n| next_election1     =\n| next_election2     =\n| session_room       =Sandyford House from Sandyford Road (geograph 3619116).jpg\n| session_res        =\n| session_alt        =\n| meeting_place      =[[Sandyford House]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n| website            = \n| footnotes          =\n| motto              =\n}}\n'''Tyne and Wear County Council''' was the [[county council]] of the metropolitan county of [[Tyne and Wear]] in north east England. It came into its powers on 1 April 1974 and was abolished on 1 April 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1987/1288/made|title=The Local Government Reorganisation (Property) (Tyne and Wear) Order 1987|publisher=Legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref> The county council was based at [[Sandyford House]] in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]. It was replaced with five authorities: [[Metropolitan Borough of Gateshead]], [[Newcastle City Council]], [[North Tyneside Council]], [[South Tyneside Council]] and [[Sunderland City Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twmuseums.org.uk/files/5578-acquisitions-and-disposal-policy-archives.pdf|title=Archives Collection, Acquisition and Disposal Policy|publisher=Tyne & Wear Archives & Museums|date=22 November 2012|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[1973 Tyne and Wear County Council election]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Former county councils of England}}\n\n[[Category:Former county councils of England]]\n[[Category:History of Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:1974 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:1986 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:Tyne and Wear|County Council]]\n\n\n{{UK-poli-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox legislature\n| name               = Tyne and Wear County Council\n| native_name        =\n| native_name_lang   =\n| transcription_name =\n| legislature        =\n| coa_pic            =Tyne-&-Wear-Flag.jpg\n| coa_caption        =\n| coa_res            =\n| coa_alt            =\n| logo_pic           =\n| logo_caption       =\n| logo_res           =\n| logo_alt           =\n| house_type         =\n| body               =\n| houses           